    "after": "NEW HOME OF GIRLS CLUBS OF AMERICA, Inc.\n\nFive-story brick and limestone town house at 133 East 62nd Street, Manhattan, which has been acquired by Girls Clubs of America, Inc., federation of girls' clubs in the United States and Canada, for its national headquarters.\n\nBuilt in 1885, the house was given an ornate limestone trim in 1900 by Robert McAllister Lloyd, pioneer electrical engineer, then owner.\n\nGirls Clubs of America, Inc., founded in 1945 in Springfield, Mass., and located in New York City for seven years, has until now occupied rented quarters.\n\nMrs. John V. Lindsay, wife of the Mayor of the City of New York, accompanied members of GCA's national board on their first visit, as owners, to their first permanent home.\n\nPhoto Gratis\nGirls Clubs of America, Inc.,\n101 Park Avenue,\nNew York, N. Y. 10017\n\nFor immediate release",
    "before": "First attached page: Letter\n--------------------------GIRLS CLUBS OF AMERICA, INC.\n101 PARK AVENUE, NEW YORK, N. Y. 10017\nTELEPHONE MURRAY HILL ?-????\n\nMay 5, 1967\n\nDirector,\nHistorical Section,\nReference Library,\n\nN.Y. Public Library\nFifth avenue-42nd street,\nNew York, NY. 10036\n\nDear Sir:\n\nHere is a copy of the print of the building at 133 East 62nd street which I promised.\n\nSincerely\nFrances Mason\nDirector\nPublic Relations\n\nSecond attached page: Press release\n----------------------------------NEW HOME OF GIRLS CLUBS OF AMERICA, Inc.\n\nFive-story brick and limestone town house at 133 East 62nd Street, Manhattan, which has been acquired by the Girls Clubs of America, Inc., federation of girls' clubs in the United States and Canada, for its national headquarters.\n\nBuilt in 1885, the house was given an ornate limestone trim in 1900 by Robert McAllister Lloyd, pioneer electrical engineer, then owner.\n\nGirls Clubs of America, Inc., founded in 1945 in Springfield, Mass., and located in New York City for seven years, has until now occupied rented quarters.\n\nMrs. John V. Lindsay, wife of the Mayor of the City of New York, accompanied members of GCA's national board on their first visit, as owners, to their first permanent home.\n\nGirls Clubs of America, Inc.,\n101 Park Avenue,\nNew York, N.Y. 10017\n",
