    "after": "Villa St. is only 4 blocks s. of the Westchester Cross County Parkway.\n\nThe present aerie of two of the old Grand Central Eagles on Villa St. Mount Vernon, N.Y. Like the Mercury on the present Grand Central they're all poised for flight but never fly.\n\nHARCOURT STRANGE\n145 Fourth Ave.\nMount Vernon, N.Y. 10550\n\nAccording to a feature article appearing in The N.Y. News Column Magazine Jan. 2, 1966 the above casting eagle was one of 16 which adorned the top of the old Grand Central Station at 42 St. N.Y.C. Those birds were added to the remodeled station in 1929 but remained on their perch for 5 years. Then were removed when the station was 'rebuilt' in 1983. The News illustrated 6 of the in their report locations: The one above and another are now on Villa St. Mount Vernon, N.Y. (over for map)  ",
    "before": "On front of photo is the caption:\n\"Photo by Harcourt Strange, 1966\"\n\nOn back of photo is a map of the area in Mount Vernon, N.Y. where the eagle depicted on the front of the photo was located.\n\nThe following 2 blocks of text appears directly on the map:\n\"Villa St. is only 4 blocks S. of The Westchester Cross County Parkway.\"\n\n\"The present aerie of two of the old Grand Central Eagles on Villa St. Mount Vernon, N.Y.  Like the Mercury on the present Grand Central they're all poised for flight but never fly.\"\n\nA return address label is attached to the map with the following on it:\nHARCOURT STRANGE\n145 Fourth Avenue\nMount Vernon, N. Y. 10550\n\nOn a separate slip of paper attached to the back of the photo appears the following:\n\"According to a feature article appearing in The N.Y. News Coloroto  [sic] Magazine Jan. 2, 1966 the above cast iron eagle was one of 16 which once adorned the top of the old Grand Central Station on 42 St. N.Y.C.  Those birds were added to the remodelled station in 1898.  But only remained on their perch for 5 years. Then were removed when the station was rebuilt in 1903. The News illustrated 9 of the 16 in their present locations. The one above and another are now on Villa St. Mount Vernon, N.Y. (over for map.)\"\n",
